<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-14">
  <title>Resources for 10/14</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain how an <em>exponential function</em> describes a quantity that either increases or decreases by a fixed percentage over some constant change in the input values (e.g. a quantity that increases by 5% every 2 years).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine the formula for an exponential function given information about the percent increase/decrease of the function and the value of the function at a given input.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Determine the formula for an exponential function given the values of the function at two given inputs.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use your understanding of exponential functions to solve application problems (e.g. interest rate [including compound interest] &amp; radioactive decay).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-exponential-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Introduction to Exponential Functions (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing <em>exponential functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="zjdlwEOtZkU" />

    <problem>
      <title>Introduction to Exponential Functions</title>
      <p>
        The following problems are to help you understand exponential functions.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              You deposit $1000 in an account earning an annual interest rate of 5%.  Interest is re-computed every year.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How much money is in the account at the end of each of the first three years?  
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    If you have $<m>A</m> in the account one year, how much money do you have in the account one year later?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use what you found in (b) to write your answers in part (a) in a different way.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use what you found in part (c) to find a formula for the amount of money <m>A(t)</m> you have after <m>t</m> years.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You are storing 100 lbs. of radioactive material in which 25% of the material decays every year.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How much material is left at the end of each of the first three years?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the amount of radioactive material <m>M(t)</m> that is left after <m>t</m> years.  Try using a similar process as we used in #1.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol> 
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you have some quantity that <em>increases</em> by a factor of <m>r</m> each year (for instance, if <m>r=0.05</m>, then the quantity increases by 5% each year).  If you start out with quantity <m>A_0</m> at <m>t=0</m>, how much quantity <m>A(t)</m> do you have at time <m>t</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you have some quantity that <em>decreases</em> by a factor of <m>r</m> each year.  If you start out with quantity <m>A_0</m> at <m>t=0</m>, how much quantity <m>A(t)</m> do you have at time <m>t</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-applications-exponential">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applications of Exponential Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>applications for exponential functions</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="64ht3QUD9ss" />

    <problem>
      <title>Exponential Applications</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following application problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we invest money in an account with a fixed annual interest rate.  After two years, we have $250 and after five years we have $400.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the amount <m>A(t)</m> that is in the account after <m>t</m> years.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the interest rate on the account?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    How much money did we start out with?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose we own something that loses a fixed percentage of its value each year.  After 3 years, it is worth $300, and after 7 years, it is worth $200.
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find a formula for the value <m>V(t)</m> that the item is worth after <m>t</m> years.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What is the annual percentage that the value drops?
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    What was it worth at the beginning?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
